{
  "local_port": 34466,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the questions asked in interviews?",
  "response": "Interviews can vary widely depending on the industry, role, and company, but there are common types of questions that are frequently asked across many job interviews. Here\u2019s a breakdown of the typical categories and examples of questions you might encounter:\n\n---\n\n### **1. General/Introductory Questions**\nThese are often used to break the ice and get to know you better.\n- Tell me about yourself.\n- Walk me through your resume.\n- Why are you interested in this role/company?\n- What do you know about our company?\n- What are your strengths and weaknesses?\n\n---\n\n### **2. Behavioral Questions**\nThese assess how you\u2019ve handled situations in the past, which is often used to predict future behavior.\n- Tell me about a time you faced a challenge and how you overcame it.\n- Describe a situation where you worked as part of a team.\n- Give an example of how you handled a conflict at work.\n- Tell me about a time you failed and what you learned from it.\n- How do you prioritize tasks when you have multiple deadlines?\n\n---\n\n### **3. Technical/Skill-Based Questions**\nThese are role-specific and test your knowledge, expertise, or technical abilities.\n- How would you approach [specific task or problem related to the job]?\n- What tools or software are you proficient in?\n- Can you explain [specific concept or process]?\n- How do you ensure accuracy in your work?\n- Describe your experience with [specific skill or technology].\n\n---\n\n### **4. Situational/Hypothetical Questions**\nThese ask how you would handle a hypothetical scenario in the role.\n- How would you deal with a difficult client or coworker?\n- If you were given a project with a tight deadline, how would you approach it?\n- What would you do if you disagreed with your manager\u2019s decision?\n- How would you handle a situation where you didn\u2019t know the answer to a problem?\n\n---\n\n### **5. Problem-Solving and Critical Thinking Questions**\nThese test your ability to think on your feet and solve complex problems.\n- How would you improve our current process/product?\n- Describe a situation where you had to make a quick decision with limited information.\n- How do you approach solving a problem you\u2019ve never encountered before?\n- What steps would you take to identify the root cause of an issue?\n\n---\n\n### **6. Cultural Fit and Personality Questions**\nThese assess whether your values and work style align with the company culture.\n- What type of work environment do you thrive in?\n- How do you handle stress or pressure?\n- What motivates you at work?\n- How do you define success?\n- What do you enjoy doing outside of work?\n\n---\n\n### **7. Career Goals and Aspirations**\nThese explore your long-term plans and how the role fits into your career path.\n- Where do you see yourself in 5 years?\n- What are your short-term and long-term career goals?\n- Why are you looking for a new role now?\n- What are you looking for in your next job?\n\n---\n\n### **8. Questions About the Company**\nThese demonstrate your interest in the organization.\n- What do you think are the biggest challenges facing the company/industry?\n- How does this role contribute to the company\u2019s goals?\n- What do you admire most about the company culture?\n- How does the company support employee growth and development?\n\n---\n\n### **9. Salary and Logistics Questions**\nThese are often asked toward the end of the interview.\n- What are your salary expectations?\n- When would you be available to start?\n- Are you open to relocating or traveling for work?\n- Do you have any questions for us?\n\n---\n\n### **10. Questions You Can Ask the Interviewer**\nIt\u2019s always good to have a few thoughtful questions prepared.\n- What does success look like in this role?\n- How would you describe the team culture?\n- What are the biggest challenges the team is currently facing?\n- What opportunities for growth and development does the company offer?\n\n---\n\n### Tips for Success:\n- Use the **STAR method** (Situation, Task, Action, Result) for behavioral questions.\n- Research the company and role beforehand.\n- Practice answering common questions, but keep your responses natural and authentic.\n- Be prepared to provide specific examples from your experience.\n\nGood luck with your interview! Let me know if you'd like help preparing for a specific type of interview or role.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
